Here's the full migration analysis and rewritten code.

## Pattern Classification

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Timeout fallback kill | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with token |
| `while (true)` loop | Cancellable work loop | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(() => RunLoop(_cts.Token));
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either the event is signaled OR cancellation is requested
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) // token.WaitHandle fired → stop requested
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes a bug in the original where
            // rapid Enqueue calls could leave items stuck in the queue)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();       // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);  // wait up to 5s for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback needed — the loop checks the token
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The token signals the loop cooperatively.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` removed** — It only works on threads in `WaitSleepJoin` state and is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9). `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` replaces it cleanly.

3. **`WaitOne()` → `WaitHandle.WaitAny()`** — The original `WaitOne()` can't be interrupted by cancellation. `WaitAny` wakes on *either* the event signal or the cancellation token.

4. **`IDisposable` added** — `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are disposable; leaking them causes timer/callback leaks.

5. **Drain loop added** — The original had a subtle bug: if `Enqueue` was called twice before `RunLoop` woke, `Reset()` cleared the signal after dequeuing only one item. The new code drains all queued items per wakeup.

## Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **`Handle()` ignores cancellation** | If `Handle()` is long-running, cancellation won't take effect until it returns. Pass the token into `Handle()` and check it periodically. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using` or call `Dispose()`. |
| **Calling `Stop()` twice** | Safe here because `Cancel()` is idempotent, but `Dispose()` is not — guard against double-dispose if needed. |
| **Expecting immediate stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints (`WaitAny`, loop condition). If `Handle()` takes 30 seconds, the thread won't exit for 30 seconds. |
